@@eThe Warden Tradition@@N

@@yThe Road Wardens@@N
The warden tradition's earliest lineage belongs to the road warden companies of the
Keeper Era: professional escorts chartered to protect caravans across the desert
road network. Wardens were paid, chartered, and legally bounded by the convoy
manifest they protected. They could not act outside their assigned corridor without
voiding their commission. This constraint shaped the tradition permanently. Warden
doctrine was never about conquest but about holding assigned ground. The discipline
required, patience under pressure, positional awareness, the capacity to absorb
damage without breaking, became the core inheritance of every martial tradition
that descended from the road companies.

@@yThe Forty-Three Days@@N
At the Seven Shade Arches, Warden-Sergeant Caleph Dunmar held a waystation for
forty-three days against an Ashbound siege, protecting a water convoy with nothing
but defensive ground and discipline. He fought near infrastructure, targeted water
carriers first, and held through attrition rather than aggression. Two of the seven
arches were permanently destroyed. The doctrine he demonstrated, fight near shade,
target logistics, hold until the objective is secured, became the foundational Ember
Warden combat doctrine still taught under his name. The five surviving arches bear
the oldest continuous inscription tradition in the warden canon: travelers carve the
date and their name, an acknowledgment that they passed through ground that held.

@@yThe Reaver Confederates@@N
When the Ninth Meridian Rite failed and the charter system collapsed, the most
cohesive road companies reorganized as the Reaver Confederates: privatized militias
who had outlived their employers. They were not brigands by self-understanding but
wardens without charters, continuing to offer protection in a world where no one
could issue valid commissions. Those who maintained protection doctrine through the
chaos became the nucleus of the first civic militias.

@@yThe Two Schools@@N
The tension between autonomous doctrine and institutional compliance defines the
modern tradition. The Dunmar School holds that discipline supersedes orders when
orders violate fundamental protective purpose. The Registry School holds that civic
legitimacy requires institutional obedience. Most wardens navigate between these
positions situationally, and the disagreement never quite breaks into open schism.
